assessment_comment: Numerous spawning sockeye immediately adjacent to culvert outlet and upstream. Channell dry at the time of assessment, but appears as though this stream joins with and drains the watershed for the stream mapped as larger located to the east approximately 1km. Flood plane modelling shows this.
link_method_phase1: Link to Methods for Fish Passage Assessment

assessment_comment: Review of flood plane mapping indicates that this watershed actually drains to 1 km West through an open bottom structure. Adjacent land use is for cattle so this may be affecting drainage and habitat health upstream.
condition_notes: Pipe is rusted all the way through at the top 1 m
climate_notes: This cover is not appear to be the main drain for this watershed. Evaluation of floodplain mapping indicates this watershed drains through the larger open bottom of structure located approximately 1 km west.
climate_priority_notes: Psycho spawning area identified to the west 1 km and five value Medina River just downstream, however does not seem likely that this crossing receives much flow indicated by the type and size Channell
link_method_phase1: Link to Methods for Fish Passage Assessment

assessment_comment: Larger stream than expected. Go to lots of flow and large outlet drop and fairly large outlet pool indicate this culvert is well undersized for the crossing. Some gravels suitable for BT spawning present.
condition_notes: Some small wood debris blocking the inlet. Large outlet drop and fairly large outlet pool in case is under size.
climate_notes: Cover appears undersized, however there appears to be a decent buffer distance between here and the likely high value habitat, located downstream in the Nadina river with no infrastructure in between
climate_priority_notes: Fish presents unknown however it is assumed based on the map gradient. Very remote no traffic road.

assessment_comment: This is the crossing on CollieyMount Road however there are also two pipes approximately 10 m west and just upstream that are likely historically were within Colleyount Road. Pipe is in poor condition with rust all the way through for the top upstream 2 m. Stream was dry at Time of assessment.
condition_notes: Covered in poor shape and rusting through, but no outlet job indicates the pipe is decently sized.
climate_notes: Lack of outlet shop indicates that the pipe is decently sized. Road is protected just upstream by parking blocks that are located at the outlet of the historic pipes just upstream.
climate_priority_notes: Stream flows through Lakes District recreation site. Cover is located approximately 50 m upstream of Francois Lake.        Assumed fish bearing during non-dry times of year due to location adjacent to the lake and low gradient

assessment_comment: This pipe as well as the overflow appear to be under what was likely the historic location of Colieymount Road. Personally, 3 to 4 m from the outlets, the road is armoured with parking blocks which direct the flow west into the oval culvert underneath the current road. Dry at time of assessment,

assessment_comment: Very nice stream with good flow and abundant, small gravel upstream and down. There is a folder line approximately 3 m downstream of the outlet that has removed all outlet drop but is a approximately 40 cm high cascade. Outlet of culvert is approximately 25 m from François lake.
condition_notes: Culvert appears to be getting old but is in decent shape. No outlet drop.
climate_notes: Culvert is 25 m upstream from François Lake
climate_priority_notes: Unpaved Road with small advance traffic, but access would be difficult or perhaps impossible via the ferry if the road was shut

assessment_comment: Large concrete box structure with the outlet directly on the flood plane of the Fraser. When the river is 2 1/2 to 3.5 m Higher the structure would backwater. Appears that the high watermark is near level with the outlet of the culvert
link_method_phase1: Link to Methods for Fish Passage Assessment

assessment_comment: Very long cover in poor shape. Outlet land on Boulder rip wrap cascade is currently dry as the water is falling out through the bottom of the eroded pipe. Downstream 50 to 100 m very large beaver dams begin. Habitat confirmation conducted downstream and upstream as well as upstream and downstream of the railway located approximately 1.5 km downstream adjacent to the Fraser river

assessment_comment:
Work was completed in 2019 to back water the outlet and remove the outlet drop as well as to put baffles within the culvert.

Routine monitoring form also filled out a can be found in accompanying report
condition_notes: No evidence of embankment eroding or damage to repairs conducted in 2019
climate_notes: No infrastructure located downstream and structure appears well
climate_priority_notes: Due to low flows in the summer stream does not appear to have overly high habitat value with salmon species, not confirmed within the system. With such a large overall system and large amount of fill replacement of a car would be a multi year endeavor.

assessment_comment: Two pipes at 2.6 m each. Pipes are in decent shape although it appears they had skirts at the outlets that have ripped off. Difficult to determine the size of the outlet drop as the stream was dry at the time of assessment.  Culvert also crosses underneath a road and powerline on the east side of the railway
